What is DSA?

DSA stands for Data Structures and Algorithms.

It is a fundamental concept in Computer Science used to organize data efficiently and solve problems with optimized logic.

Data Structures → Ways to store and organize data

Algorithms → Step-by-step procedures to solve problems

Example:
If you want to search a number in a list, different algorithms can do it faster or slower.

Data Structures in JavaScript

JavaScript already provides some built-in structures and you can also implement classic ones.

1. Array

Used to store multiple values in order.

let arr = [10, 20, 30];
console.log(arr[1]); // 20
2. Object

Stores data in key-value pairs.

let user = {
  name: "John",
  age: 25
};

console.log(user.name);
3. Stack (LIFO – Last In First Out)
let stack = [];

stack.push(10);
stack.push(20);
stack.pop(); // removes 20
4. Queue (FIFO – First In First Out)
let queue = [];

queue.push(10);
queue.push(20);
queue.shift(); // removes 10
5. Linked List

A chain of nodes connected with pointers.

Example concept:

10 → 20 → 30 → null
6. Hash Table

Fast key-value storage.

JavaScript versions:

Object

Map

let map = new Map();
map.set("name", "Alex");
7. Tree

Hierarchical structure.

Example:

       10
      /  \
     5    20

Common type: Binary Tree

8. Graph

Used for networks (social networks, maps).

Example:

A ---- B
|      |
C ---- D
Algorithms in JavaScript

Common algorithms used in DSA:

Searching

Linear Search

Binary Search

Sorting

Bubble Sort

Selection Sort

Insertion Sort

Merge Sort

Quick Sort

Example (simple search):

function linearSearch(arr, target) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (arr[i] === target) {
      return i;
    }
  }
  return -1;
}
